<font color="#FF0000">IS IT HEALING?</font><br>
<tt>Sun May 11 21:00:13 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Somewhere around 1980, working as a paramedic, we responded to a drowning case in a home pool. We arrived and found a four year old pulled from the pool. Cooly and efficency we worked on that kid. We couldn't start an IV, so I had a cop drag a physician from a local clinic to start a cutdown. The ER physician wanted to call the code several times and pronounce the boy dead, but I insisted that we keep at it. That was the longest &quot;Code Blue&quot;, probably on the books for a paramedic unit as I kept it up for three hours. It wasn't till the drugs in our box and those in the van were depleted and the batteries in the LifePak 4 were expired, that I allowed the code to be called. <br><br>
We went back to our quarters, cleaned our equipment, restocked everything, then proceeded to our favorite resturant for breakfast. In the middle of hotcakes and sausages, it hit me. I felt nothing for that child. Not a blessed thing. Right then and there, I knew it was time to get out.<br><br>
Chet and Gerald, don't let this happen to you! Tom, you are right, the rucksac becomes an unwielding burden. Something might need to be done.<br><br>
On the other hand, could this be what it means to be &quot;healed&quot;?
<p><code>-- docdel@maui.net  (Doc Del) </code><p>


